09261nam a22012135i 9783110664058DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20212021gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2020949158  a97831106640587 a10.1515/97831106640582doi  a(DE-B1597)522183  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aBUS0810002bisacsh00aExploring non-human work in tourism :bFrom beasts of burden to animal ambassadors /ced. by Carol Kline, Jillian M. Rickly. 1aMünchen ;aWien : bDe Gruyter Oldenbourg, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (VIII, 275 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aDe Gruyter Studies in Tourism ;v500tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgements -- tContents -- t1 Introduction: Working for the (hu)man in the tourism industry -- tPart 1: Theoretical considerations -- t2 Conceptualizing non-human animals as “workers” within the tourism industry -- t3 Redefining the work of working animals in the tourism industry: An animal-centric reflection -- tPart 2: Performative work -- t4 Working donkeys in northwestern Mexico: Urban identity and tourism resources -- t5 Animal dark tourism in Mexico: Bulls performing their own slaughter -- t6 Farm animals’ participation in tourism experiences: A time for proper respect -- tPart 3: Value-added work -- t7 Animals as tourism stakeholders: Huskies, reindeer, and horses working in Lapland -- t8 Distributed leadership in tourism experiences: Russian sled dogs and Icelandic horses leading the way -- t9 A working holiday: From home to destination with a guide dog -- t10 The donkeys of Santorini: Workers or slaves? -- t11 Monkey see, monkey do: The work of primates in Costa Rican sanctuaries -- t12 The greening of polar bears: Lively commodities in a climate change economy -- t13 “Cute, but get up and work!”: The biophilia hypothesis in tourists’ linguistic interactions with pandas -- tPart 5: Reflections -- t14 Working animal research: An agenda for the future -- t15 Afterword: On tourism, animals, and suffering – lessons from Aeschylus’ Oresteia -- tList of contributors -- tList of figures -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCritical animal studies is increasingly interfacing with tourism research in an effort to shed light on the various ways animals are incorporated into touristic experience. Exploring non-human work in tourism: From beasts of burden to animal ambassadors builds upon the theoretical connections of animal ethics, agency, and welfare as it foregrounds specifically the work that animals perform in the industry. While some types of animal labor are more readily identified, readers of this volume may be surprised by how many forms of animal labor are overlooked. Taking a widely international perspective, with cases from the Arctic, China, Costa Rica, China, Finland, Greece, Mexico, New Zealand, and the United Kingdom, this volume offers readers diverse scenarios of animals working. The book is arranged along three themes of work. Performative work focuses on the animals whose performances are front and center of tourists’ motivations and experiences. Value-added work turns attention to the co-working relationships of animals, while the political work of animals as ambassadors and icons is examined within the chapters on hidden labor. Additionally, the book makes theoretical considerations of the implications of positioning animals as workers and offers reflections on ways this focus on working animals extends current scholarship in the field.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Industries / Hospitality, Travel & Tourism.2bisacsh  aAnimal sport (or racing).  aAnimal welfare.  aPack animal.  aService animal.  aWorking animal.1 aAndersson Ceder